","after 1420":"na 1420","1405":"1405","Lewynsmede, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"1400–after 1420":"1400–after 1420","1400–1420":"1400–1420","1405–1498":"1405–1498","1411–Male":"1411–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1400–1442":"1400–1442","1420–1490":"1420–1490","1425–Male":"1425–Deceased","1377–1411":"1377–1411","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1380":"1380","1490":"1490","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1411":"1411","1377":"1377","1498":"1498","24 July 1411":"24 July 1411","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1419":"1419","after 1420":"after 1420","1405":"1405","Lewynsmede, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>s(c)hawe</i>, <i>s(c)haghe</i> ‘small wood, grove, thicket’ (Old English <i>sceaga</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a small wood, or habitational, for someone from any of the many places so named. <i>Shaw</i> and <i>Shawe</i> are most frequent in Lancashire and Yorkshire, where Shaw in Oldham (Lancashire) may be a principal source of the surname. The English and Lowland Scottish surname was also established in Ireland in the 17th century.","Scottish: shortened form of various surnames from the Gaelic personal name <i>Sitheach</i>, derived from <i>sithech</i> ‘wolf’.","Irish (Down and Antrim): adopted for <b>Ó Síthigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’. Compare   Sheehy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Show","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cumberland): probably a variant of   Shaw  , perhaps representing a blend in Middle English of Old English <i>sceaga</i> and Old Norse <i>skógr</i>, both meaning ‘wood’.","Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Schau  ."]},{"name":"Sheehy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Aisling, Brigid, Declan, Egan, Eoin, Finbar, Ronan.","Irish (Limerick and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Síthigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, or <b>Mac Síthigh</b> ‘son of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a form of the Irish personal name <i>Síodhach</i> ‘peaceful’, from the adjective <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’ or ‘other worldly’ (see   Sheehan  ). The noun <i>síth</i>, from which this adjective derives, means basically ‘settlement’, hence both ‘peace’ and ‘place inhabited by other world beings’. This name was established in Ireland from the early 14th century, when a branch of the Scottish McDonnells, descended from <i>Sítheach</i>, great-grandson of Domhnaill, settled in the country."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mary Alice Shaw was born in 1400, in Gloucestershire